---
import Layout from '@/components/astro/Layout.astro';
import { AlertCircle, CheckCircle, XCircle, TrendingUp, Users, FileText, Building } from 'lucide-react';

const pageTitle = 'When Should Your Texas Business Hire a Lobbyist? The 7 Signals You Can\'t Ignore';
const pageDescription = 'Here\'s what most business owners miss: the best time to hire a lobbyist is before you need one. Experienced Texas lobbyist Byron Campbell reveals the critical signals that it\'s time to engage political representation.';
const publishedDate = '2025-01-03';
const author = 'By Byron Campbell, Texas Lobbyist';
const category = 'Strategy';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BlogPosting',
  headline: pageTitle,
  description: pageDescription,
  datePublished: publishedDate,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: 'Byron Campbell'
  }
};
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} schema={schema}>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-texas-blue-50 via-white to-background py-20 lg:py-28 border-b border-border">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <div class="mb-8">
        <a
          href="/blog"
          class="inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-600 hover:text-texas-blue-700 transition-colors group"
        >
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 mr-2 transition-transform group-hover:-translate-x-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M10 19l-7-7m0 0l7-7m-7 7h18" />
          </svg>
          Back to all articles
        </a>
      </div>

      <div class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-texas-blue-500/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-700 mb-6">
        {category}
      </div>

      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-bold mb-6 leading-tight tracking-tight">
        When Should Your Texas Business Hire a Lobbyist?
      </h1>

      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-muted-foreground mb-10 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        The typical mistake: waiting until a bill threatens your operations before hiring a lobbyist. By then, you've missed the most effective window for influence and tripled your costs.
      </p>

      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-6 text-sm text-muted-foreground border-t border-border pt-6">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">{author}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M8 7V3m8 4V3m-9 8h10M5 21h14a2 2 0 002-2V7a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v12a2 2 0 002 2z" />
          </svg>
          <time datetime={publishedDate}>
            {new Date(publishedDate).toLocaleDateString('en-US', {
              month: 'long',
              day: 'numeric',
              year: 'numeric'
            })}
          </time>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">10 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <article class="py-16 lg:py-20">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">

      <!-- Introduction -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Here's what catches businesses off guard: the worst time to hire a lobbyist is when you desperately need one. By the time a bill is filed that threatens your business model, your options are limited, your costs are higher, and your probability of success is lower.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Effective lobbying isn't crisis management. It's strategic relationship-building that happens months before a problem emerges. The best lobbyists I know spend more time in coffee shops during the interim than in committee rooms during session—that's where the groundwork gets done.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          So when should your business hire a lobbyist? There are seven clear signals. If you're seeing any of these, you're already later than ideal—but not too late to get positioned strategically.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Signal 1 -->
      <section id="signal-1" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Signal #1: You're Hearing Rumors About Legislation</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">Third-hand information means you're behind</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            "I heard they might pass a bill requiring..." If you're getting legislative intelligence at industry conferences or through trade association emails, you're receiving stale information. The real action happens months earlier.
          </p>

          <p>
            Bills are drafted during the interim—often with input from stakeholders who've positioned themselves early. By the time a bill is filed in January, the language has been negotiated, committee assignments have been discussed, and opposition has been mapped. If you're just hearing about it when it hits the press, you've missed the most valuable intervention window.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
              <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-2 mb-3">
                  <XCircle className="h-5 w-5 text-red-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900">Red Flag Approach</h3>
                </div>
                <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-red-800">
                  <li>• Relying on industry newsletters for legislative intel</li>
                  <li>• Learning about bills when they're filed</li>
                  <li>• Hearing rumors at conferences</li>
                  <li>• Waiting for trade associations to sound alarm</li>
                  <li>• No direct Capitol intelligence</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-2 mb-3">
                  <CheckCircle className="h-5 w-5 text-green-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-green-900">Strategic Approach</h3>
                </div>
                <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-green-800">
                  <li>• Lobbyist monitors interim committee hearings</li>
                  <li>• Direct relationships with legislative staff</li>
                  <li>• Advance warning before bill drafting</li>
                  <li>• Opportunity to shape language early</li>
                  <li>• Positioned before session starts</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            The difference between hearing about a bill in November versus January is the difference between shaping the language and fighting finished text. One costs $50,000 and often succeeds. The other costs $150,000 and usually fails.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Signal 2 -->
      <section id="signal-2" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Signal #2: Your Industry Is Under Political Scrutiny</h2>
          <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">When politicians start talking, legislation follows</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Are legislators holding hearings about practices in your industry? Is the Attorney General launching investigations? Are consumer advocacy groups filing complaints and getting media coverage?
          </p>

          <p>
            Political attention creates legislative momentum. What starts as a hearing about "concerns" in your sector becomes a bill draft by next session. I've watched this cycle play out dozens of times—industries that ignore early warning signs end up fighting defensive battles they can't win.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 bg-amber-50 border-2 border-amber-400 rounded-lg p-6">
            <div class="flex gap-3 mb-4">
              <AlertCircle className="h-6 w-6 text-amber-700 flex-shrink-0" />
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-900 mb-2">Real Example: Short-Term Rentals</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 mb-3">
                  In 2017-2018, neighborhood associations started complaining about Airbnb-style rentals disrupting residential areas. Hotels joined in, arguing about unfair competition. Local news ran investigative pieces.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 mb-3">
                  Companies that hired lobbyists during this interim period worked with legislators to draft reasonable regulations that balanced neighborhood concerns with property rights. They got a seat at the negotiating table.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-amber-900">
                  Companies that waited until bills were filed in 2019? They fought defensive battles, spent twice as much, and got less favorable outcomes.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            The key insight: political scrutiny during the interim is your early warning system. Hire representation before that scrutiny crystallizes into legislation. Proactive lobbying can defuse pressure, provide data that changes the narrative, and position your industry as part of the solution rather than the problem.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-3">
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-5">
              <p class="text-sm font-bold text-foreground mb-1">Warning Sign: Interim hearings mentioning your sector</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Committee chairs exploring issues for next session</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-5">
              <p class="text-sm font-bold text-foreground mb-1">Warning Sign: AG enforcement actions in your industry</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Creates legislative appetite for new regulations</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-5">
              <p class="text-sm font-bold text-foreground mb-1">Warning Sign: Advocacy groups targeting your practices</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">They're laying groundwork for legislative campaigns</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-5">
              <p class="text-sm font-bold text-foreground mb-1">Warning Sign: Media investigations highlighting problems</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Creates political pressure legislators respond to</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Signal 3 -->
      <section id="signal-3" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Signal #3: You're Expanding Operations in Texas</h2>
          <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">Growth creates regulatory exposure and opportunity</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Opening your first Texas facility? Scaling from 50 employees to 500? Seeking tax incentives for a major capital investment? Growth increases your political visibility—which creates both risk and opportunity.
          </p>

          <p>
            When you're small, you fly under the political radar. When you're employing hundreds of Texans and investing millions in facilities, you become a constituency. Legislators want to help job creators—but they also expect you to navigate the political landscape professionally.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-blue-900 mb-3">What a Lobbyist Does for Expanding Companies</h3>
            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-blue-900">
              <div class="flex gap-3">
                <Building className="h-5 w-5 text-blue-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                <div>
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Navigate Economic Incentives</p>
                  <p>Help you access Chapter 313 tax abatements, enterprise zone benefits, and local economic development deals. These programs have political gatekeepers—your lobbyist knows them.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="flex gap-3">
                <FileText className="h-5 w-5 text-blue-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                <div>
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Expedite Permitting and Licensing</p>
                  <p>When you need special permits or regulatory approvals, having relationships with agency leadership and legislative oversight committees accelerates timelines.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="flex gap-3">
                <Users className="h-5 w-5 text-blue-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                <div>
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Build Relationships with Local Delegation</p>
                  <p>Introduce you to legislators representing the districts where you operate. These relationships pay dividends when you need support on local or statewide issues.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            I've worked with companies that treated lobbying as part of their market entry strategy—budgeting for it alongside legal fees and facility costs. They secured better incentive packages, smoother permitting processes, and stronger legislative relationships than competitors who tried to DIY their government relations.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-green-500 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-green-900 mb-3">Growth Triggers That Warrant Lobbying Investment</h3>
            <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-green-800">
              <li><strong>Major capital investments:</strong> Manufacturing plants, data centers, distribution facilities ($50M+)</li>
              <li><strong>Significant employment growth:</strong> Hiring 200+ employees in Texas markets</li>
              <li><strong>Seeking economic incentives:</strong> Tax abatements, grants, infrastructure support</li>
              <li><strong>Complex permitting needs:</strong> Environmental permits, special licenses, regulatory approvals</li>
              <li><strong>Multi-market expansion:</strong> Opening facilities in 3+ Texas cities</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Signal 4 -->
      <section id="signal-4" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-purple-50 border-l-4 border-purple-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Signal #4: Your Competitor Just Hired a Lobbyist</h2>
          <p class="text-purple-700 font-medium">Unilateral disarmament is not a winning strategy</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            You can verify this in about 10 minutes. Texas Ethics Commission records show who's lobbying for which companies. If your competitors are investing in political representation and you're not, they're working to write rules that favor their business models over yours.
          </p>

          <p>
            I've seen this play out in brutal detail. Incumbent companies lobby for licensing requirements that create barriers to entry. Large operators push regulations that favor scale over agility. Industry leaders seek technical standards that happen to align with their current practices.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-400 rounded-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-3">What Happens When You Sit Out</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-red-800 mb-3">
                Your competitors aren't lobbying to ban you—that's too obvious. They're lobbying for "common-sense reforms" that happen to disadvantage your business model.
              </p>
              <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-red-900">
                <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-3">
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Scenario 1: Licensing Requirements</p>
                  <p class="text-xs">Established providers lobby for new licensing rules. They already have licenses. You don't. Now you face 18-month delays and compliance costs to enter the market.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-3">
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Scenario 2: Technical Standards</p>
                  <p class="text-xs">Industry association (dominated by large incumbents) proposes equipment standards. They've already invested in compliant systems. You'd need to retrofit.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-3">
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Scenario 3: Regulatory Exemptions</p>
                  <p class="text-xs">Competitors seek exemptions for business models identical to theirs—but slightly different from yours. You're regulated. They're not.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            The competitive intelligence value alone justifies the investment. Your lobbyist monitors what other companies in your sector are pushing for, who they're meeting with, and what amendments they're proposing. You can't defend yourself against threats you don't see coming.
          </p>

          <p>
            You don't necessarily need to match their investment dollar-for-dollar. Sometimes the smart move is joining industry coalitions to pool resources. But sitting out entirely while competitors shape the rules? That's choosing to lose.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Signal 5 -->
      <section id="signal-5" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Signal #5: You're Facing Regulatory Problems Without Legislative Solutions</h2>
          <p class="text-blue-700 font-medium">When agencies can't help, you need statutory fixes</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            You've appealed to the agency. You've submitted comments during rule-making. You've met with senior staff. The answer is still no—not because they're being difficult, but because the statute ties their hands.
          </p>

          <p>
            Some problems can't be solved at the agency level. The law says what it says, and regulators can't ignore it no matter how sympathetic they are to your situation. When the underlying statute is the problem, you need legislation to fix it.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">Common Statutory Problems</h3>
              <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-muted-foreground">
                <li><strong>Outdated technology assumptions:</strong> Laws written before your business model existed (think: Uber vs. taxi regulations)</li>
                <li><strong>Conflicting agency jurisdiction:</strong> Two agencies claiming authority over the same issue, creating regulatory limbo</li>
                <li><strong>Overly broad restrictions:</strong> Statutes that ban beneficial practices along with harmful ones</li>
                <li><strong>Arbitrary thresholds:</strong> Requirements that made sense 20 years ago but don't fit modern operations</li>
                <li><strong>Unintended consequences:</strong> Laws that inadvertently prohibit reasonable business activities</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            Legislative fixes are multi-session endeavors. Changing statutes takes time—often 2-4 years from concept to passage. You need to start early, build relationships with relevant committee chairs, educate staff about the problem, and line up coalition support.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-400 rounded-lg p-6">
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <TrendingUp className="h-6 w-6 text-yellow-700 flex-shrink-0" />
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-yellow-900 mb-2">The Honest Timeline</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-yellow-900 mb-3">
                  <strong>Year 1 (Interim):</strong> Identify problem, draft concept, meet with committee staff, build coalition, educate legislators
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-yellow-900 mb-3">
                  <strong>Year 2 (Session):</strong> File bill, navigate committee process, manage amendments, (hopefully) pass one chamber
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-yellow-900">
                  <strong>Year 3-4:</strong> If bill died, restart process with lessons learned and broader support
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            If you're hitting regulatory walls, hire a lobbyist now—not in January when session starts. The groundwork happens during the interim. By the time session convenes, successful bills already have committee support lined up and opposition neutralized.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Signal 6 -->
      <section id="signal-6" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-indigo-50 border-l-4 border-indigo-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Signal #6: You're Planning to Sell Your Business</h2>
          <p class="text-indigo-700 font-medium">Regulatory risk kills deals and crushes valuations</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            When businesses first prepare for a sale, they often overlook this critical factor: buyers conduct political risk due diligence. They want to know what legislative threats could undermine the business post-acquisition. Pending legislation creates valuation uncertainty—and uncertainty kills deals.
          </p>

          <p>
            I've watched deals fall apart because buyers discovered regulatory threats the seller wasn't even monitoring. I've also seen valuations get discounted by millions because pending legislation created "material uncertainty" about future operating conditions.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-indigo-500 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-indigo-900 mb-4">What Buyers Look For in Due Diligence</h3>
              <div class="space-y-4">
                <div class="bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <p class="text-sm font-bold text-indigo-900 mb-2">Regulatory Risk Assessment</p>
                  <p class="text-sm text-indigo-800">Are there pending bills that could restrict operations? Is the industry facing political pressure? What legislative threats exist?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <p class="text-sm font-bold text-indigo-900 mb-2">Government Relations Maturity</p>
                  <p class="text-sm text-indigo-800">Does the company monitor legislative activity? Have relationships with key legislators? Participate in industry advocacy?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <p class="text-sm font-bold text-indigo-900 mb-2">Political Intelligence Capability</p>
                  <p class="text-sm text-indigo-800">Can the company identify threats early? Respond effectively to regulatory changes? Navigate agency relationships?</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            Having a lobbyist on retainer signals to buyers that you're sophisticated about managing political risk. It's not just about defending against current threats—it's demonstrating that the business has systems in place to navigate future regulatory changes.
          </p>

          <p>
            If you're planning an exit in the next 2-3 years, add lobbying to your pre-sale preparation checklist alongside financial audits and legal cleanup. The cost is tiny compared to the valuation impact of unmanaged political risk.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Signal 7 -->
      <section id="signal-7" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-rose-50 border-l-4 border-rose-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Signal #7: You're Being Asked to Testify or Provide Input</h2>
          <p class="text-rose-700 font-medium">Direct engagement requires professional support</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            A legislative staffer emails asking for input on draft legislation. A committee chair invites you to testify at an interim hearing. The governor's office requests data about your industry for a policy report.
          </p>

          <p>
            Congratulations—you've been identified as a stakeholder. These invitations are opportunities, but they're also tests. How you respond shapes your credibility and relationships for years to come. Amateur hour testimony or poorly crafted written comments can damage your standing with legislators and staff.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 bg-rose-50 border-2 border-rose-400 rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-rose-900 mb-3">Why You Need a Lobbyist Before Testifying</h3>
            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-rose-900">
              <div class="flex gap-2">
                <CheckCircle className="h-5 w-5 text-rose-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                <div>
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Navigate Committee Dynamics</p>
                  <p>Your lobbyist knows which members are friendly, which are hostile, and what questions to expect. They prep you for the political dynamics, not just the policy.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="flex gap-2">
                <CheckCircle className="h-5 w-5 text-rose-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                <div>
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Craft Effective Written Testimony</p>
                  <p>Format, length, framing, supporting data—there's a formula for effective legislative testimony. Get it wrong and your comments go in the trash.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="flex gap-2">
                <CheckCircle className="h-5 w-5 text-rose-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                <div>
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Coordinate with Allies</p>
                  <p>Who else is testifying? Are you aligned? Contradictory testimony from natural allies destroys credibility. Your lobbyist manages coalition coordination.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="flex gap-2">
                <CheckCircle className="h-5 w-5 text-rose-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                <div>
                  <p class="font-bold mb-1">Follow Up Appropriately</p>
                  <p>Testimony isn't the end—it's the beginning. Effective follow-up with committee staff and members is what converts testimony into influence.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            Being invited to the table is valuable only if you show up prepared and credible. A lobbyist ensures you make the most of these opportunities rather than squandering them with amateur mistakes.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Cost Reality -->
      <section id="cost-reality" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
